<paragraph blockId="35.[160,1155,1348,1513]" box="[160,409,1348,1374]" pageId="35" pageNumber="300">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,409,1348,1374]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="300">External morphology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[160,1155,1348,1513]" pageId="35" pageNumber="300">Body elongate, narrow, background colour white and semi-transparent with digestive branches of dark green. Cerata long, smooth; background colour dark green, with white punctuation, apex white. Rhinophores long, translucent white with green branches and white punctuation on tips.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="300" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="35.[160,1155,1564,1728]" box="[160,252,1564,1590]" pageId="35" pageNumber="300">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,252,1564,1590]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="300">Ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[160,1155,1564,1728]" pageId="35" pageNumber="300">
Specimens found on the green alga 
<taxonomicName authority="(J. V. Lamouroux, 1809)" baseAuthorityName="J. V. Lamouroux" baseAuthorityYear="1809" box="[606,1074,1599,1624]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Bryopsis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="35" pageNumber="300" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mucosa">
<emphasis box="[606,794,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="300">Bryopsis mucosa</emphasis>
(J.V. Lamouroux, 1809)
</taxonomicName>
laying cylindrical and white egg masses. Specimens in this study were found within a few centimetres’ depth feeding on 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="J. V. Lamouroux" baseAuthorityYear="1809" box="[548,670,1669,1694]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Bryopsis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="35" pageNumber="300" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mucosa">
<emphasis box="[548,670,1669,1694]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="300">B. mucosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is commonly found at subtidal depths.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
